s contests dominant definitions of the human. The theorizations of race and disability that emerge from these works, Pickens demonstrates, challenge the paradigms of subjectivity that white supremacy and ableism enforce, thereby pointing to the potential for new forms of radical politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aAfrican Americans with disabilitieszUnited States. 0aAfrican AmericansxStudy and teaching. 0aAmerican fictionxAfrican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aDisability studieszUnited States. 0aDiscrimination against people with disabilitieszUnited States. 0aMinority people with disabilitieszUnited States. 0aPeople with disabilities in literature. 0aPeople with disabilitieszUnited States. 0aRace in literature. 0aScience fiction, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / African-American.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2019z978311069632540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478005506zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478005506423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478005506.jpg  a978-3-11-069632-5  DUK eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles